Gotcha—let’s add a super‑simple “debug dump” so every change‑feed document gets written to Blob Storage as a plain JSON file you can open in Portal/Storage Explorer.

Below is drop‑in Java code (SDK v12.31+) that:
	•	builds a safe blob name: <logicalContainer>/<docId>/<yyyy-MM-ddTHH-mm-ssZ>.json
	•	writes the raw change‑feed ObjectNode as UTF‑8
	•	sets Content-Type: application/json
	•	adds a few handy index tags (optional) so you can filter by id/container in Portal
	•	never throws (it logs and returns), so it won’t break your function while you debug

1) Helper: DebugDumpToBlob.java

package com.neo.notification.blob;

import com.azure.core.util.Context;
import com.azure.storage.blob.BlobContainerClient;
import com.azure.storage.blob.models.BlobHttpHeaders;
import com.azure.storage.blob.models.BlobStorageException;
import com.azure.storage.blob.options.BlockBlobSimpleUploadOptions;
import com.azure.storage.blob.specialized.BlockBlobClient;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ObjectNode;

import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;
import java.time.OffsetDateTime;
import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.UUID;
import java.util.logging.Logger;

/** Writes every incoming change-feed doc to a debug area in Blob for easy viewing. */
public final class DebugDumpToBlob {

    private static final ObjectMapper MAPPER = new ObjectMapper();

    private DebugDumpToBlob() {}

    /** Dump a raw change doc to blob. Never throws—logs errors and returns. */
    public static void dump(
            BlobContainerClient debugContainer,
            String logicalContainer,
            ObjectNode changeDoc,
            Logger log) {

        try {
            if (changeDoc == null) {
                log.warning("DebugDumpToBlob: changeDoc was null; nothing to write.");
                return;
            }

            // id may be missing in some change-feed shapes; fall back to a GUID
            String docId = changeDoc.hasNonNull("id")
                    ? changeDoc.get("id").asText()
                    : "no-id-" + UUID.randomUUID();

            // filename-safe timestamp (replace ':' so it’s portal-friendly)
            String ts = OffsetDateTime.now().format(DateTimeFormatter.ISO_INSTANT).replace(":", "-");

            // Path example: CustomerContainer/123/2025-08-13T12-34-56Z.json
            String blobPath = logicalContainer + "/" + docId + "/" + ts + ".json";
            BlockBlobClient blob = debugContainer.getBlobClient(blobPath).getBlockBlobClient();

            byte[] payload = MAPPER.writeValueAsString(changeDoc).getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);

            // Nice to have for viewing
            BlobHttpHeaders headers = new BlobHttpHeaders()
                    .setContentType("application/json; charset=utf-8");

            // Optional: index tags so you can search in Portal by id/container
            Map<String, String> tags = new HashMap<>();
            tags.put("logicalContainer", logicalContainer);
            tags.put("docId", docId);
            tags.put("kind", "debug");
            tags.put("writtenAt", ts);

            BlockBlobSimpleUploadOptions opts = new BlockBlobSimpleUploadOptions(payload)
                    .setHeaders(headers)
                    .setTags(tags);

            blob.uploadWithResponse(opts, null, Context.NONE);
            log.info("DebugDumpToBlob: wrote " + blobPath);

        } catch (BlobStorageException bse) {
            log.severe("DebugDumpToBlob: storage error " + bse.getErrorCode() + " / " + bse.getMessage());
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            log.severe("DebugDumpToBlob: unexpected error " + ex.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

2) Call it from your trigger (inside your loop)

Assuming you already have a BlobContainerClient for a debug container (use your existing singleton provider). If not, you can temporarily reuse your data container too.

// at top of the function method (once)
final BlobContainerClient DEBUG_CONTAINER =
        BlobClientProvider.container(System.getenv("DebugContainerName")); // e.g., "debug"

// inside your for (ObjectNode newDoc : documents) loop, first line:
DebugDumpToBlob.dump(
        DEBUG_CONTAINER,
        cosmosDbContainerName,   // the logical Cosmos container name
        newDoc,
        context.getLogger());

3) App setting

Add one setting in your Function App (and local.settings.json while local):
	•	DebugContainerName = debug  (create a “debug” container in your storage account)

That’s it. Now every change shows up under the debug container with a folder per logical container and per id. Open the JSON directly in the Azure Portal to see exactly what the trigger received.